7 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
8 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
9 Article – Public Utilities
10 4–212.
11 (c) (1) (i) On or before September 1, 2026, each investor–owned electric
12 company and each electric cooperative shall submit to the Commission for approval a
13 specific rate schedule for large load customers that accomplishes the intent of subsection
14 (b) of this section.
15 (ii) Each municipal electric utility that receives an application for
16 retail electric service from a large load customer shall submit to the Commission for
17 approval a specific rate schedule for large load customers.
18 (2) (i) Service under a specific rate schedule shall be available to large
19 load customers that will use, within the initial contract term:
20 1. a monthly maximum demand of more than [100] 25
21 megawatts at a single location; or
22 2. an aggregated contract capacity in the electric company’s
23 service territory of more than 100 megawatts.
24 (ii) Except as provided in subparagraph (iii) of this paragraph, large
25 load customers that qualify for a specific rate schedule after the effective date of that
26 schedule:
27 1. shall take service under the specific rate schedule; and
28 2. may not be allowed to take service under any other
29 existing schedule.
30 (iii) A specific rate schedule does not apply to the facility of an
31 existing large load customer that has signed a service agreement before the effective date
32 of the schedule if:
33 1. the large load customer’s existing load does not expand by

HOUSE BILL 1532 3
1 more than 25 megawatts at that facility under the existing service agreement; or
2 2. the large load customer does not sign a new service
3 agreement to expand the facility’s load by more than 25 megawatts above the contract
4 capacity of the existing service agreement.
5 4–213.
6 (a) This section applies only to a public service company that is an electric
7 company, a gas company, or a combination gas and electric company.
8 (b) Unless otherwise authorized by law, the Commission may approve the use of
9 a multiyear rate plan for distribution base rates only if the plan:
10 (1) demonstrates the customer benefits of the investment; and
11 (2) does not allow for:
12 (I) the public service company to file for reconciliation of cost or
13 revenue variances of the approved revenue component used by the Commission to establish
14 just and reasonable rates IF THE RECONCILIATION WOULD RESULT IN ADDITIONAL
15 CUSTOMER CHARGES; OR
16 (II) THE USE OF COST–SHARING MECHANISMS THAT WOULD
17 RESULT IN ADDITIONAL CUSTOMER CHARGES ABOVE THE APPROVED REVENUE
18 COMPONENT USED BY THE COMMISSION TO ESTABLISH JUST AND REASONABLE
19 RATES.
20 (c) A public service company that files or has filed an application for a multiyear
21 rate plan may not subsequently file for reconciliation of cost or revenue variances [of] THAT
22 WOULD RESULT IN ADDITIONAL CUSTOMER CHARGES DUE TO THE PUBLIC SERVICE
23 COMPANY SPENDING MORE THAN the approved revenue component used by the
24 Commission to establish the multiyear rates unless the filing for reconciliation was made
25 on or before January 1, 2025.
26 (D) THE COMMISSION MAY REQUIRE A PUBLIC SERVICE COMPANY TO
27 INCLUDE A RECONCILIATION PROCEDURE IN ITS MULTIYEAR RATE PLAN TO REFUND
28 CUSTOMERS THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN:
29 (1) THE PUBLIC SERVICE COMPANY’S FORECAST REVENUE
30 REQUIREMENT; AND
31 (2) THE PUBLIC SERVICE COMPANY’S ACTUAL REVENUE
32 REQUIREMENT DURING THE TERM OF THE MULTIYEAR RATE PLAN.

