28 7–1216.
29 (a) The Commission may not approve an application for a nuclear energy
30 generation project submitted under § 7–1212 of this subtitle unless:

HOUSE BILL 1532 9
1 (1) the project is connected to the electric system serving the State;
2 (2) over the duration of the proposed long–term pricing schedule, the
3 projected net rate impact for an average residential customer, based on annual
4 consumption of 12,000 kilowatt–hours and combined with the projected net rate impact of
5 other nuclear energy generation projects, does not exceed an amount determined by the
6 Commission;
7 (3) over the duration of the proposed long–term pricing schedule, the
8 projected net rate impact for all nonresidential customers, considered as a blended average
9 and combined with the projected net rate impact of other nuclear energy generation
10 projects, does not exceed a percentage determined by the Commission of nonresidential
11 customers’ total annual electric bills; and
12 (4) the price specified in the proposed long–term pricing schedule does not
13 exceed an amount determined by the Commission.
14 (b) When calculating the projected net average rate impacts for nuclear energy
15 generation projects under this section, the Commission shall [apply the same] CONSIDER
16 THE net long–term cost per megawatt–hour APPLIED to residential and nonresidential
17 customers.
18 7–1220.
19 (a) In this section, “zero–emission credit” means [the difference between the price
20 that a nuclear energy generating station with a long–term pricing schedule approved in an
21 order issued under § 7–1217 of this subtitle may receive on the wholesale market and the
22 cost of constructing the nuclear energy generating station] A CREDIT EQUAL TO THE
23 ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT OF 1 MEGAWATT–HOUR OF ELECTRICITY THAT IS
24 DERIVED FROM A NUCLEAR ENERGY GENERATING STATION APPROVED BY THE
25 COMMISSION UNDER § 7–1217 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
26 (b) The Commission shall adopt regulations that:
27 (1) establish the nuclear energy long–term pricing purchase obligation
28 sufficiently in advance to allow an electric company to reflect nuclear energy long–term
29 pricing costs as a nonbypassable surcharge that is added to the electric company’s base
30 distribution rate on customer bills;
31 (2) define rules that facilitate and ensure the secure and transparent
32 transfer of revenues and long–term pricing payments among parties;
33 (3) define the terms and procedures of the nuclear energy long–term
34 pricing schedule obligations, including:

10 HOUSE BILL 1532
1 (i) establishing a formula and process to adjust the value of the
2 long–term pricing schedule every 2 years based on projected wholesale market prices
3 adjusted by the locational value and earning potential in the PJM region of the nuclear
4 energy generating station; and
5 (ii) establishing a per megawatt hour cap on any long–term pricing
6 schedule specified in an order issued under § 7–1217 of this subtitle;
7 (4) require the Commission to establish an escrow account; and
8 (5) to meet the total statewide long–term pricing purchase obligation for
9 all applications approved in an order issued under § 7–1217 of this subtitle, require the
10 Commission to annually establish each electric company’s zero–emission credit purchase
11 obligation based on the most recent final electricity sales data as reported by PJM
12 Interconnection and measured at the customer’s meter in proportion to the electric
13 company’s share of statewide load.
14 (c) (1) Each electric company shall procure from the escrow account
15 established by regulation under this section a quantity of zero–emission credits equal to
16 the electric company’s respective percentage of retail electric sales each year.
17 (2) Subject to any escrow account reserve requirement the Commission
18 establishes, if there are insufficient zero–emission credits available to satisfy the electric
19 companies’ zero–emission credit purchase obligations, the overpayment shall be distributed
20 to electric companies to be refunded or credited to each distribution customer based on the
21 customer’s consumption of electricity supply that is subject to the renewable energy
22 portfolio standard.
23 (d) A debt, an obligation, or a liability of a nuclear energy generation project or of
24 an owner or operator of a nuclear energy generation project may not be considered a debt,
25 an obligation, or a liability of the State.
26 (E) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE
27 COMMISSION MAY APPROVE AN INCREASE OF THE TOTAL COST OF A NUCLEAR
28 ENERGY GENERATION PROJECT UNDER A LONG–TERM PRICING PURCHASE
29 OBLIGATION.
30 (2) THE TOTAL COST OF A NUCLEAR ENERGY GENERATION PROJECT
31 UNDER A LONG–TERM PRICING PURCHASE OBLIGATION MAY NOT BE INCREASED BY
32 MORE THAN 15% OF THE ORIGINAL COST.
33 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
34 (a) (1) On or before July 1, 2026, the Public Service Commission shall issue a
35 request for information on the use of a third–party, single–implementer program for the
36 administration of the programs and services under Title 7, Subtitle 2, Part II of the Public

HOUSE BILL 1532 11
1 Utilities Article.
2 (2) The request for information shall seek:
3 (i) determinations of what effect the use of a single, third–party
4 administrator would have on costs;
5 (ii) identification of technical and logistical barriers to transitioning
6 to a single, third–party administrator; and
7 (iii) an analysis of the advantages and disadvantages of a private,
8 third–party administrator as opposed to a State administrator.
9 (3) The request for information shall specify a completion date of July 1,
10 2027.
11 (b) (1) Within 30 days after receiving the information requested in subsection
12 (a) of this section, the Public Service Commission shall issue a request for proposals for a
13 third–party administrator for the programs and services under Title 7, Subtitle 2, Part II
14 of the Public Utilities Article.
15 (2) The request for proposals shall specify that responses to the request
16 should minimize short–term and long–term costs for utility ratepayers.
17 (c) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, on or before June
18 1, 2028, the Public Service Commission shall select, through the request for proposals
19 process initiated under subsection (b) of this section, a third–party administrator for the
20 administration of the programs and services under Title 7, Subtitle 2, Part II of the Public
21 Utilities Article.
22 (2) (i) The Public Service Commission may decline to select a
23 third–party administrator if the Public Service Commission determines that the use of a
24 third–party administrator would not be cost effective.
25 (ii) The Public Service Commission shall notify the General
26 Assembly of a decision to decline to select a third–party administrator within 5 days after
27 making the decision.
28 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
29 (a) The Power Plant Research Program, in consultation with the Department of
30 the Environment and the Maryland Energy Administration, shall conduct a study to
31 identify ways to streamline the permitting process for energy development in the State.
32 (b) In conducting the study under subsection (a) of this section, the Power Plant
33 Research Program shall:

12 HOUSE BILL 1532
1 (1) identify up to 50 priority energy sites suitable for new or expanded
2 generating stations or energy storage devices, including:
3 (i) brownfields;
4 (ii) industrial sites surrounded by areas with low–population
5 density; and
6 (iii) sites with old or decommissioned generating units that may be
7 repowered or repurposed, with special consideration given to sites with surplus
8 interconnection capacity;
9 (2) identify current bottlenecks and barriers in the State that extend State
10 and local permitting timelines; and
11 (3) develop recommendations on what a State–level zoning or permitting
12 structure should look like in order to promote fast–tracked development at the priority
13 energy sites identified in item (1) of this subsection.
14 (c) On or before December 31, 2026, the Program shall report to the Governor
15 and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the General Assembly
16 on the results of the study.
17 SECTION 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
18 1, 2026.

